  "prompt": "Is money laundering considered an illegal practice?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is considered an **illegal practice** in virtually all jurisdictions worldwide. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (or \"dirty money\") appear legitimate by disguising its true origin. This is typically done through a series of complex transactions or financial maneuvers to make the funds appear as though they come from a legal source.\n\nMoney laundering is illegal because it facilitates criminal activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, terrorism financing, and other illicit operations. By disguising the source of funds, money launderers undermine the integrity of financial systems, evade taxes, and enable further criminal behavior.\n\nMost countries have strict laws and regulations against money laundering, and it is actively prosecuted by law enforcement agencies and financial regulators. Penalties for money laundering can include hefty fines, imprisonment, and seizure of assets. Additionally, financial institutions are required to implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures to detect and report suspicious activities.",
